    "answer_id" : 43640674,
    "question_id" : 43628423,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Yes, it is guaranteed that <code>s.toString() == s</code>.</p>\n<p>See <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se25/html/jls-1.html#jls-1.4\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Java Language Specification §1.4 – Relationship to Predefined Classes and Interfaces</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>[S]ome classes have a special relationship with the Java programming language. Examples include classes such as Object, Class, ClassLoader, <strong>String</strong>, Thread, and the classes and interfaces in package java.lang.reflect, among others. This specification constrains the behavior of such classes and interfaces, but does not provide a complete specification for them. <strong>The reader is referred to the Java SE platform API documentation.</strong></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>So the Javadoc of those classes (which is the &quot;Java SE platform API documentation&quot;) is normative and part of the overall spec. And that <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/25/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/String.html#toString()\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">states explicitly</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><code>public String toString()</code></p>\n<p>This object (which is already a string!) is itself returned.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>There's no room for interpretation.</p>\n<hr />\n<blockquote>\n<p>Out of interest is a &quot;deep copy&quot; taken?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>In old Sun/Oracle/OpenJDK Java before version 8, <a href=\"https://github.com/openjdk/jdk7/blob/master/jdk/src/share/classes/java/lang/String.java#L110\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">the implementation of String</a> had internal <code>int offset</code> and <code>int count</code> fields. This optimization made <code>substring</code> very fast by sharing the internal char array. But it also allowed a memory leak: a small string could potentially keep a reference to a large array. What if you needed an independent instance, a deep copy? As seen in that implementation, the (undocumented) rule was that the constructor <code>new String(s)</code> could be used to make a deep copy. However, <code>toString()</code> was identical to today: simply <code>return this;</code> – they couldn't have done anything else while being compliant with the wording &quot;This object [...] is itself returned&quot;.</p>\n<p>Even subtle changes to the behavior of widely used classes can cause wide breakage, so <code>String.toString()</code> is not going to change.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I've been brought up to regard <code>toString()</code> as an arbitrary serialisation, perhaps representative of the object, but not necessarily so.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I'd say there are two flavors of <code>toString()</code> methods. Objects which represent a value which has an exact and unembellished stringification will return that string. This includes <code>Integer</code>, <code>BigDecimal</code>, <code>Boolean</code>, <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/25/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/CharSequence.html#toString()\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">all</a> <code>CharSequence</code>s (which <code>String</code> implements). At the other extreme, objects which are complex stateful components do not have an obvious string representation. They may return a formatted summary of their major fields, or nothing special at all. Always check the Javadoc to see what, if anything, the class promises.</p>\n"
  } ],
